snippet.textDisplay:
It's a Korean car, so some of those "quirks" probably come from that fact. You joke about the party trick aspect of the parking system, but extremely tight spaces are common in Korea, especially in claustrophobic parking garages in the cities. I think a lot of the rationale for some of these features come from this driving environment or meeting customer demands/expectations. Same goes with marketing and branding, "Smartstream" may mean nothing to you, but I'm pretty sure it's mentioned by every salesman in Seoul to potential customers 😂

And apparently it works, it's supposedly the best selling car in Korea now.

Same goes with marketing and branding, "Smartstream" may mean nothing to you, but I'm pretty sure it's mentioned by every salesman in Seoul to potential customers 😂

And apparently it works, it's supposedly the best selling car in Korea now.

snippet.textDisplay: 6:50 - the blind spot camera was done best by Honda - so far - but only in the Accord (the Civic and their mini-van did it poorly, even though they used the same camera) - and Honda only did it on one side. Part of what it takes to be the 'best,' and safest, in the blind spot camera category is that the display needs to be as high up as possible without blocking too much of the windshield. The idea, and how it works in practice, is that you don't want drivers taking their eyes off of the traffic just in front of them for too long. With a high central display (i.e. NOT what Hyundai has done here), a driver can glance at the lanes beside them (via the wide-screen-camera's display) while easily maintaining traffic ahead of them in their peripheral vision. You don't want drivers looking down, or down and over, but instead to keep their eyes as close to the range of the windshield as possible. ... In my opinion, even the Accord's turn-signal-camera display wasn't enough - it still wasn't high enough to be perfect, but auto makers seem very afraid to put such a potentially useful and SAFE driving tool up where it belongs. Perhaps they are afraid of losing sales to very short people who wouldn't be able to see over a higher display?
